 fit; also guaranteed to hold their shape until worn out,\nPAY LESS AND DRESS BETTER..\n1 .V\nWe Are Exclusive Agents' for-,\nREGAL SHOES\nTHE HABERDASHERY.\nMAIM STREET A\n'r-vv\nTo!day\nYour Choice\nk.\n\nALLEN BLOCK\nfind satiated gratification\nOVP6i\nlimp by unwise speculation\n\nBREWERY AVENUE, LOWELL.\nMAIN STREET\nIs (Stated That Cases Against\nRosenthal Will Be Brought\nTo Attention of the Next\nGrrid Jury.\nAt 4 o'clock yesterday afternoon\nLouis Rosenthal, convicted by a, Jury\non Friday afternoon of having com\nmitted Indecent exposure, was sen\ntenced to serve six months In .the\ncounty jail at Tombstone and pay a\nfine of $180. He was committed to\nthe\"\"brancn county jail, pending trans\nfer to Tombstone this morning. It Is.\nprobable that the attorneys .for the\ndefense will make, an attempt to ob\ntain a release on a writ, of habeas\ncorpus\", plan9 for such action having\nbeen made yesterday.\nOn Friday night after the verdict w,\nthe jury was rendered the attorneys\nfor the defense gave notice that on\nyesterday at 11 o'clock they would\nfile motion to set aside the verdlct-l\non the ground that one of the jury-\nl men. after being sworn in, had been\nallowed to separate from the others.\nYesterday morning Assistant District\nAttorneys Ross and Taylor were on\nhand to resist any such motion, but\nthe defense did not file it.\nDuring the afternoon a rumor be-,\ncame current that Rosenthal Intend\ned to forfeit his ball bond of $500,\nand get out ot the city before the\ntime of passing sentence arrived, but!\nat 4 o'clook tba prisoner arrived in\ncourt, and it was found that the ru\nmor had been circulated by A. J.\nHepner, his room mate, who was\nalso arraigned in court .yesterday\nmorning on a charge of indecent ex\nposure. Because of the helnousness of the\noffense, and the disgusting detalb the\ncourt gave the prisoner the limit in\njail sentence, and in addition imposed\nthe. fine. v\nIt was learned last evening that it\nis very probable an effort will be\nmade\" to have' the prisoner Indicted\nof a felony charge at the next ses\nsion of the grand jury, as several\nother Instances where Jie has annoyed\nla'die3 of the cfty and subjected them\nto Indignities have been brought to\nlight.\nWhen asked about the matter be\nfore leaving for his home. \"In Douglas\nlast evening Assistant District At\ntorney Ross said:\n\"At the present time It is Impossi\nble to tell, what action will be taken\nagainst Rosenthal. It is very prob\nable that he will have,to serve out the\njail sentence wb.lch.Sas been Imposed,\nwhich will give the Jistrict attorney's\noffice time to investigate the -various\nother cases in which he is alleged to\nhave committed the same Offense, and\nI can assure you that the most severe\naction warranted by the premises will\nbe taken.\"\n0 t\nHEALTH OF GUY\nEpidemics of Grip and Small\nPox Are Checked Typhoid\nCases Unusual,-\nWith tlje milder weather that has\nprevailed In this section recently and\nwith no new cases of small pox hav\ning appeared for the past three\nweeks, from a health standpoint the\ncondition of the city is much more\nsatisfactory. The epidemic of grip\nwhich had so many in Its grasp for\na, tlmehas also 'about spent Itself,\nalthough there are' quite a number\nwho are Just recovering from its at\ntack. There are at present only two\ncases of small pox in the city, both\nof which are In the detention camp.'\nUntil yesterday there were three,\nMiss Alice Purl having been dismiss\ned as entirely .well. The other two\npatients are rapidly convalescing\nand wiH be able to leave the camp\nin a short .time. Inasmuch \"as It only\ntakes two -weeks' for the disease to\ndevelop and .there; havo\" been no new\ncases for the past three weeks, the\nhealth authorities are hopeful that\nIts spread has been thoroughly check\ned.\nFor a wMo there were quite a num\nber of pneumonia cases in the city,\nmany of, -which developed from at\ntacks of grip, \"but these, too, are very\nfew now, with practically no new\ncases Teported. The fonr case3 ot\ntyphoid, fever,, .all confined to one\nramlly are very unusual and there\nIs little probability of the disease\nspeadlng at this time of ths year,\nas the germs' are rarely able to -live\nIn the cold weather of winter.\nReview Want Ads Bring Results.\nCananea Is again taking the lead\nIn baseball circles and' will soon-have\na team ready to contest for honors\nwith any team in this section ot the\ncountry. As was announced In the\nReview several days ago, the team\nhas already been secured and they\nare, expected. In the Mexican city some\ntime during this week, to get In prac\ntice\" for 'the season.\nThree of-the' players have been\ndrafted. from this city Dugan, Chit\ntendon and Arnold. They will leave\nIn a day or two for Cananea to re\nport fort. practice. Rinehart, who is\nwell known, lri \"baseball circles to\nthis part of the territory. Is expected\ndally from Houston to join the Cana\nnea team. Rinehart has spent the\npast winter In the Texas clt\nThose Interested In the Cananea\nteam say' that she will be, abje'ttys\nyear to give fully as good an account\nof .herself as she did last, which Is\nsaying considerable. The fans at\nCananea are promised their first ex\nhibition of they' national game about\nthe 15th ot March, and are confident\nthat a3 soon as two or three games\nhave been played that various towns\nwhich are large \"enough to support a\nteam will get busy and organize a\nbunch of ball tossers to represent\nthem against the other teams of the\nterritory.\nWALKS 280 MILES\nIN SIX-DAY RACE\nHoagland of New York Gets Big\nEnd of Purse,\nKANSAS CITY, Feb,-29. W. A.\nHoagland, of Auburn, N. Y., won the\nsis day walking match which endeo.\nhere, tonight. He covered the 280\nmiles in 62 hours. He retains .the\nworld's championship. J. E. Blake,\nof Florida, and C. F. Floyd, of Colum\nbus, Ohio, dropped out' tonight, leav\ning but five men to divide the purse.\nScore: Hoagland, 280; Tom Slater,\n.276j H. O. Messier, 272; H. L Player,\n268; Hartley. 258.\nCALLON ROOSEVELT.\nWASHINGTON, Feb. 29. W. S.\nStone, grand chief of the Brotherhood\nof Locomotive Engineers, and E. W.\nHurley and F. A. Burgess, assistant\ngrand chiefs bf the same organization,\naccompanied by Charles' P. Nelll,\ncommissioner of labor, called on the.\npresident today. They said they did\nnot discuss the railroad question.\n1 m\nGraft In Old New York.\"\nThe first use of the -word \"graft\" In\nHew York occurred 250 years ago. A\nmall stream that led froma swamp\nthrough what Is now Broad street was\nma,de Into a ditch with the sides plank\ned to form what Is known in Holland\nas a \"graft\" or a canal. Three labor\ners were employed on this job by the\nburgomasters, and a committee of five\nwas appointed to supervise their oper\nation and see that they gave -full\nvalne for their pay. The completed\ngraft was turned over to the under\nsheriff with 'these orders: \"He is or\ndered to take good care and superin\ntendence of the newly constructed\ngraft and also that the boats, canoes\nand skiffs be authorized to operate\ntherein.\"\no\nOrigin of \"Blackleg.\"\n\"Blackleg\" has become so familiar\" In\nits special, labor application that this\nIs now more- common even than the\nuse of ,the \"word in Its original sense\nBut labor so far' has not shortened\n\"blackleg\" to \"leg,\" as the sporting\nworld has in speaking of sharpers.\nHowV'blackleg' came by its swindling\nsignificance Is a puzzle which even an\nargument before the full court of\nqueen's bench In a libel case failed to\nsolve. It has been traced to the for\nmer habit among turf frequenters of\nwearing black topboots, but others\nhave seen an allusion to the legs of\ngamecocks. .Trades unionism adopted\nit simply as a term of abuse, like\n\"scab.\" London Chronicle.\nStradlvarlns -wastforn in, Cremona.\nItaly, in the year i&i&. To make vio\nlins was his sole and only business, his\njoy, his religion. He died In 1737. leav\ning behind hlni three sons, who tried\nto carry on their father's business, but\nfailed to bring their work cp to the\nBaxter's standard,\nTo Tell Pure Coffee.\nDenmark Is fatrfons fortts coffee, as\nevery tourist to that fascinating coun\ntry\" can bear witness. A Banish wo\nman who lives In New York was\nspeaking ..of cotfoe the other day. tell\ning how to distinguish ths various\ngrades. She .took up a cup of \"cafe\nnolr\" and, tilting It gently, asked her\nvis-a-vis tot examine the side of the\ncup closely.\n\"It leaves a brown mark,. doesn't It?\"\nher companion remarked.\n\"Yes, It' does.\" the Dane replied,\n\"and that's one good, way of telling'\nwhether It Is pure coffee or not. The\nreal article always leaves this mark\neven on. the most delicate porcelain.\nYour adulterated stuff doesn't. Thls Is\nall right.\" New York Press. J\nDelivered the Qoodt.\nok here!\" said the angry patron\nt the restaurant\" man. \"You've got a\nsign out there that says, 'Coffee like\nmothernsed to make.'. Yon arc a swin\ndler, sir! This Is the sllmslest, weak\nest, dlshwatcrlest apology for coffee\nthat I ever tasted.\"\n\"Yes,, sir,\" replied the serious look'\ning .restaurant man. \"But ifs the kind\nmy mother nsed to make. The sign\ndoesn't specify any particular mother,\nyou know. We are on the square here,\nsir, as you will find on Inquiry, Call\nagain.\" Chicago Post.\no\nBy bringing your job work to th\nReview you get the best servica.\nOFFICERS:\nU C. 8HATTUCK, President\nJ. M. MUHEIM, VIca Pre&denL\nJ. H. HOOD, Cashier.\nE. W. SPIERS, Asst Cashier.\nC. A. BENNETT, Mgr. Lowell Branch.\nEjilly equipped\nDRAFTS SLILL OUT\nIssued During Time of Strin\ngency and Have Not Yet\nBeen Returned,\nAlthough the local mining compan\nies several months ago discontinued\nthe practice of paying their employes\nIn drafts drawn on their New York\nbankers and made payable to bearer,\nwhich, was made necessary by the\nfinancial stringency, there are still a\nnumber Kot the drafts outstanding,\nand there seenw to b.e no disposition\non the part of the holders to sur\nrender them.\nAt ths time of the financial panic\nIn New York when the banking insti\ntutions ot that city were forced to\nadopt the clearing house rule be\ncause of the wild stampede of peo\nple, who had lost faith in almost ev\nerthing and were desirous of having\ntheir money in coin, .and the\" conse\nquent adoption of the rule through\nout the country, the local mining\ncompanies for the convenience of\ntheir employes adopted the draft sys\ntem. According to this employes, were\npaid the same as usual, but instead\nof receiving cash received denomina\ntional drafts drawn on New York\nbanks which were received In the\ncourse of business in the district at\ntheir full face value.\nThese drafts circulated the samo\nas money, and in due time the major\nity of theln found their way Into New\nYork,- and were retired from circu\nlation. However there are still out\nstanding a number of these drafts\nand the officials of the company are\ndesirous of having them presented so\nthat the owners can receiye their full\nface value In cash, and the emer\ngency checks can be retired. No doubt\nsome of these drafts have been lost\nor destroyed and will never be cash\ne.V L\n'WILL OPEN TODAY\nNew Management Will'Serve\n.Dinner Tomorrow Prom\nise f;east of Good Things,\nWhat promises to be one ot tne\nmost attractive' and best equipped\ncafes that has been opened in .this\nsection of the country, will tocay\nthrow its doors open to the public\nfor the first time. We refer to, the\nRoyal Hotel, which, has recently pass\ned to the management of Messrs. Ger\nmain and Tong, who have thoroughly\nrefitted it (throughout and .made It\none of the most desirable rooming\nand eating places In the city. $The\ndining room especially has been sub\njected to'a thorough renovation ana\nrefitting and has been furnished In. a\nmanner suitable to its use.\n.Mr. Germain, who' has' special\ncharge of the cafe, Is\", as ias been\nannounced before, one of the best\ncheTs to be found anywhere and pre\nsided in that capacity over the presi\ndential kitchen during the last ad-\nminlstratlon' of President Cleveland.\nHe ha3 .secured a competent set of\nwaiters and will himself give per\nsonal attention' 'to the cuisine service.\nHe announces that tomorrow evening\nfrom' 5:30 to' S;00\" he will serve the\nbest SO cent dinner that has ever\nbeen prepared' in the' 'city. 23\nsjNro\nThe\nAt Bisbee, In the Territory\ni\nResources..\n'Loans' and Discounts 'less due'Irom Dl\nrector p t\n-Due from' Directors ..'\"..'j.V.\nOverdrafts .....i.\nDue from Trust Companies, State and\nNational Banks\nBanking House, Furniture and .Fixtures\nOther Real Estate\nBonds and 'Warrants ....,,..4\nCurrent Expenses and. Taxes Paid;\nLsgal Tender and.National Bank-Notes\nFxchanga'for Clearings\nOther Items' carried as ca3h\nTotal\n.Territory of Arizona, 'County of Cochlses. r\nI, M. J. .Cunningham, Cashier of tho 'above named bank do solemnly\nis true to the' best of my\" knowledge and belief. w. ':i V\nyi.\nCorrect Attest:\nSubscribed-and sworn to-beforo me this 27th day of February-1908.\n(Smll\nMy commission .expires 'April 1,\ndirectors:\nl. c. bhattuck,\njacob schmid,\nl. j. overlook,\nj. t: hood,\nJ. M. MUHEIM.,\nto do anything in\nBRITT-NELSON\n0\nFIGHT PICTURES\nto be shown In Bisbee,\nMonday and Tuesday evenings and\nat the second show only the Brltt\nNelson ght pictures will be 3hown\nat the Theatre Royal, and the Bis\nbee public will have the opportunity\nto decide for themselves whether\nBrltt's claim \"that he lost the Colma\nby a fluke or chance blow\" was a\nJust one. Wherever these pictures\naro shown this point causes a great\ndeal of discussion.\nThl3 is unquestionably the greatest\nreproduction of the greatest strugglo\never witnessed for the lightweight\ncrown. You will see. the most mar\nvelous pictures ever produced by\nphotographic art. You will see every\nthing that any man or woman saw\n41 the (ringside at Colma. Not a.\nsingle detail is lacking.\nThe, great crowd moves before you\nwith wonderful realism. It is the\nmost wonderful triumph of photo\ngraphic science, far outstripping any\nthing ever known before.\nWhen the fighters enter the ring,\nand when they join in combat, yrfu\ncan almost hear the thud of blows, so\nfaithful are these pictures to the\ntruth. These pictures are of special\ninterest at present, as Britt and Nel\nson will battle for the fourth time\nin Los Angeles on Tuesday evening\nnext It is a notable fact that\nwherever these' pictures have been\nshown that the bigger portion of the\nattendance was composed of ladles.\nThe film shows the entire eighteen\nrounds and knockout, being \"5,000 feet\nin length, and shows such well known\npeople as James J. Jeffries and his\nwife, George Siler'and his wife, Ed\ndie Graney. James W,. Coffroth, John\nR. Daly, \"Nat C. Goodwin, Billy\nNolan Wlllus Britt, Spider Kelly,\nHarry Corbett, Billy Jordan, etc.\nThe pictures will be explained\nthroughout by a competent lecturer,\nwho was at the ringside during the\ncontest\nThe Iris Theatre Company have se\ncured these pictures for four days\nonly and at a great expense, conse\nquently will have to change 25 and\n50 cents. The first 15 rows will be\nreserved at 50c. and the last seven\nrows will be the -25c. or general ad\nmission seats. Reserved seats were\nplaced on sale Thursday and are go\ning fast These pictures were shown\nin. Lowell last evening, to a packed\nhouse, and now all the-' ladies are\nwondering why so many people say\nthat prize fighting 13 brutal.\nThese pictures will be shown In\nDouglas tonight, and after being\nshown in Bisbee will he put on ex\nhibition In Cananea Wednesdaj and\nThursday.\no\nDOUGLAS NEyfS NOTES.\n(Douglas International Amer'cau.l\nSecretary W. D. Eastman yesterday\nreceived word from an old friend of\nthe name of JRepp. a mining engineer\nat a camp about five miles from Can.\nanea, whom Mr. 'Eastman did not\nknow was in this part of the country\nand whom he had not seen for a\nlong time, telling him that Repp is\nvery ill and asking the secretary to\ncome to him at once.\nResponding to this call, Mr. East\nman went to Naco on the afternoon\ntrain today and from there with\nparty- of mining men will proceed Dy\nautomobile to Cananea. He' would\nhave gone on the early train today\nbut by accident missed it\nHe Is' very solicitous about the con\ndition ot his friend.\nW. S. Gentry, for more than rwo\nyears a patrolman of the local-police\ndepartment, will, after March 1 pros\nably discontinue his service with the\ncity. Officer Gentry has himself made\nthe statement about town that he has\nbeen told his services will end. at. that\ntime. Marshal Stambaush Is non-com\nmittal about the matter but does' not\ndeny that Gentry's, connection\" with)\nREPORT OF THE CONDITION OF\nBank of Bisbee\nof Arizona;, at the close of business February 14, 1908.\nCapital Stock paid\n536,099.88 Surplus\n17fM0.no TTndtvMed Profits\n7,999.13 Individual Deposits Subject to Check\nDemand Certificates' of Deposit\n492,04851 Cashier'3 Checks outstanding\n56,616.84 Duo to Trust Companies, State and\n8.000.00 Natfonal-,Banks\n138,386.67\n-4,785.85\n90,858.01\n48,756.00\n10,748.47\n4,992.43\n\n..$i;414,29L73. Total\nW.HBROPHY\nJ. ,;S. DOUGLAS J\n-V4\n\n.191.1.\nS\nj\nthe Banking line\nBANKOF BISBEE HAS\nEXCELLENT REPORT\nDespite Recent Financial Panic\nIf Offers Best Statement\nIn History.\nThe statement of the Bank of Bis\nbee, which was published yesterday\nunder a call from the territorial bank\nexaminer is the best showing ever\nmade by this pjoneer \"bank of Bisbee.\nThe total asset3 of the bank are $1,\n414,291.79. and the Individual deposits\nare shown to be Jl.197,374.07. This\nis certainly a most flattering showing\nand speaks for itself regarding the\nprosperity of the bank and the con\nfidence It enjoys in this section of\nthe territory. Such a statement\nnot only shows tho stability of the\nBank of Bisbee, but it also speaks\nin loud tones for the prosperity of\nBisbee.\nAccording tos the published state\nment this bank Is carrying more than\n$600,000 in cash in. Its vaults and on\ndeposit In other banks. This 13 mor\nthan fifty per cent ot the deposit ac\ncounts. The annual -meeting- of. .the. .stock\nholders of the Bank of Bisbee will\nbe held' tomorrow and certainly the\nofficers of the bank will have a right\nto be proud of tho- excellent showing\nthey wilt make in their report to ttie\nstockholders.\n\nTOUR OF THE \"WHITE SOX.\"\nCHICAGO, I1L, Feb. 29 What Is be\nlieved to be the greatest training trip\never taken by a baseball league club\nbegan today with tho departure of the\nChicago team of the American league\nfor Los Angeles. The magnitude of\nthe undertaking can be imagined from\nthe fact that the two sections of the\nsquad will cover nearly 15,000 miles\nbefore they return to Chicago to open\nthe season, April 14.\nThe club, accompanied by many\npress representatives and a delegation\nof enthusiastic fans, makes the trip\nin a special train that 'is one of the\nfinest that ever pulled out Of Chicago.\nThe-train is due In Kansas City to\nmorrow morning and' will' reach E1\nPaso at 5 p. m., Monday. From El\nPaso the (rain will proceed direct\" to\nLos Aneeles, which city will' be\nreached Tuesday evening! Both sec\ntions of the team will play games in\nLos Angeles and San Francisco, and\none or the other of the teams will be v\nseen in' Oakland, VlsaliaV Santa. Bar-\nbara, Salinas and Bakersfield.\n.Practically' every state in the south\nwest and the majority bf the southern\nand middle western states will be in\nvaded by one or the other of the\nsquads during the month that will be\nspent in jumping from city to city on\nthe return trip from southern Califor\nnia. Among the points where games\nhave bfcen scheduled are New Orleans,\nMontgomery, Birmingham, Nashville,\nDouglas, El Paso, Albuquerque, Okla-.\nhoma City, Hutchinson, Wichita, To\npeka, Kansas City,. .Lincoln, Sroux\nCity, Omaha, Des Moines and Burling\nton. Closer home stops will, be made ,to\nallow exhibition games at Evansvine,\nTerre Haute, Indianapolis, Cincinnati,\nSouth Bend, Champaign, Ft Waycr,\nGalesburg, Peoria, Bldomlngton, De\ncatur and Springfield.\nthe police department ends with this\nmonth.\nIt is rumored that his retirement ;s\nnot at all voluntary and It Is also\nrumored that Gentry will demand an\ninvestigation by a committee of'tne\ncity council.\n\nReview- Want Ads. bring results.\nIs;\nJ\nLiabilities.\nin ..?..T.r\n.w.ooo.oo.\n50,000.83\"\n89;921.38\n1-.197.374.07\n8,051.40\n9,727.71\n9,217.23\nf J\n,V:-5 tj\nA\n.$1,4149L79V\n\nswear, that the above statement\n\nJ.. CUNNINGHAM, Cashier.\nDlrec\nDirectors\nE. C. COREY, Notary PubllCj\nf, ,A w\n4&\n9v\n-V\n4:\ny\n1\nMil","height":"27348","width":"21328"}}
